title: For Sale:  Norinco RARE NHM-91 RARE MINT LIKE NEW IN BOX! Original Factory Box/Papers
postcontent: Scarce Norinco NHM-91!!! The Condition of this piece is EXTRAORDINARY with no signs of being used or even fired that we can see. It appears to still be in the factory Grease throughout. See Pics and Judge. It comes with the Original Box and Accessories. The NHM-91 was a semi-automatic civilian development of the Russian Kalashnikov AKM and RPK infantry small arm built by Norinco of China and marketed in the U.S. by China Sports Inc. of Ontario, California (CSI Ont, CA). A civilian semi-auto variant of the Russian AKM (Chinese Type 56) rifle, the NHM-91 was built to imitate the appearance of the Russian RPK light machine gun. First imported and marketed in the United States in 1991 by ChinaSports Inc. Based on the Russian RPK light machine gun, the NHM features a stronger receiver and a longer, thicker-profile chrome-lined barrel measuring 20 inches (508mm) compared to the 590 mm (23.2 in) of the original RPK, along with a forward-mounted steel bipod. Like the RPK, the NHM-91 utilizes a heavier-gauge stamped sheet metal receiver built from 1.5mm-thick stamped sheet metal instead of the 1mm thickness typical of a Soviet or European AKM. The NHM-91 has the long barrel, but features a milled, slant cut receiver. The longer, heavier barrel reduces shot dispersion and gives the NHM-91 rifles a longer sight radius, again resulting in improved accuracy over the typical semi-auto AKM. Trigger pull weight is also lighter than other AK designs, and some users report the rifle capable of 2-2.5 minutes of angle accuracy or better with factory 7.62×39mm ammunition. A must have for any collector!

title: For Sale:  VERY FINE - Winchester Model 1873 44-40
postcontent: Winchester Model 1873 rifle, Chambered in the highly desirable .44-40 cartridge, 24" full octagon barrel, full magazine. Made in 1884. This is a really good untouched example with only honest wear. When I first picked this rifle up, I thought the noise inside the butt stock was from a set of cleaning rods. But much to my surprise, three vintage 44-40 cartridges fell out when I opened the trap door. Who knows how long they were in there! These will be included with the rifle, but will be shipped separately. Receiver is a pleasant mix of bright original blue/plum patina/and silvery worn areas. Bright original blue has good coverage, but is more prevalent in protected areas. Barrel has 80% original bluing with the balance turning plum. Mag tube retains an original plummy brown old patina with brighter bluing in protected areas. Barrel has some scratches and dings. Bore is very good for an early black powder era Winchester with a mix of shine and corrosion with defined rifling. Bore rates 7/10 in my opinion. Wood is very good with excellent fit. Butt stock has numerous light dings, scratches and bruises from use. The LH side of the butt stock has a long scratch as shown in the photos. This may appear as a crack, but it does not extend to the butt plate. LH side of the forearm has a hairline crack as shown. Overall, the wood condition matches the rest of the rifle well. Action locks up tight and is very crisp for an antique 1873. Dust cover is exceptionally tight. A nice, honest example of an 1873 in the best caliber! Packed and shipped with care.
